<div id="review_3196239967" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3196239967" />
    <a title="Jenn Phizacklea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38485473-jenn-phizacklea"><img alt="Jenn Phizacklea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624764917p2/38485473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3196239967?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenn Phizacklea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenn Phizacklea" href="/user/show/38485473-jenn-phizacklea">Jenn Phizacklea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781849016094" href="/book/show/10616389-catilina-s-riddle">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3196239967" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4383678245965389415">This was a marked improvement on the first two books of this series, though the opening chapters, full of the elements I’ve least enjoyed in this series so far did not bode well - but the book steadily improved from there.<br/>The story travelled along at a really good pace, with plenty of twists and turns along the way; the characterisation of Catilina was brilliant, as was Cicero. I really loved the way the events, well known to me, were unfolded to the reader in a way that made them feel fresh and</span>
  <span id="freeText4383678245965389415" style="display:none">This was a marked improvement on the first two books of this series, though the opening chapters, full of the elements I’ve least enjoyed in this series so far did not bode well - but the book steadily improved from there.<br />The story travelled along at a really good pace, with plenty of twists and turns along the way; the characterisation of Catilina was brilliant, as was Cicero. I really loved the way the events, well known to me, were unfolded to the reader in a way that made them feel fresh and interesting. The mystery I solved pretty quickly, but that didn’t matter because the other events were what really carried this story.<br />I will say that I found the battlefield business, towards the end of the book, faintly ridiculous. Would either of them have survived, really? That pushed the whole ‘Fortuna was watching over us’ thing just a bit too far for me; as did the deal struck with the neighbour; but those are small complaints. This was a genuinely good read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4383678245965389415" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


