<div id="review_2427641908" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2427641908" />
    <a title="Mark Knowles" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60884899-mark-knowles"><img alt="Mark Knowles" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626383471p2/60884899.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2427641908?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Knowles" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Knowles" href="/user/show/60884899-mark-knowles">Mark Knowles</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2427641908" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16503864894196222928">I have read a fair bit of Saylor&apos;s work and enjoy it immensely. This book, however, isn&apos;t his best. &apos;Murder in the Appian Way&apos; is. There were moments in this one when I really began to feel invested in both character and plot. However, there were too many moments of &apos;tell&apos; and not enough &apos;show&apos;. I have read Cicero&apos;s &apos;in Carolinam&apos; speeches quite closely as I have had to teach them. Whilst Saylor has done a reasonable job paraphrasing them in the context of Catiline&apos;s plot, they&apos;re too static and</span>
  <span id="freeText16503864894196222928" style="display:none">I have read a fair bit of Saylor's work and enjoy it immensely. This book, however, isn't his best. 'Murder in the Appian Way' is. There were moments in this one when I really began to feel invested in both character and plot. However, there were too many moments of 'tell' and not enough 'show'. I have read Cicero's 'in Carolinam' speeches quite closely as I have had to teach them. Whilst Saylor has done a reasonable job paraphrasing them in the context of Catiline's plot, they're too static and really slow the pace down. The headless corpses provide some mystery, and there is a bit of a twist at the end, but there's too much narrative to make this truly memorable.<br /><br />Mark Knowles, author of 'The Consul's Daughter'</span>
  <a data-text-id="16503864894196222928" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


