<div id="review_1875989770" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1875989770" />
    <a title="Chandini" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5761201-chandini"><img alt="Chandini" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1875989770?book_show_action=true">Jan 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chandini" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chandini" href="/user/show/5761201-chandini">Chandini</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312385293" href="/book/show/3375707-catilina-s-riddle">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=i-own">i-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=rome">rome</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=crime">crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=italy">italy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5761201-chandini?shelf=military">military</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1875989770" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1286421970789632479">Though this is not one of the typical Roma Sub Rosa books where a client hires Gordianus to solve a murder or other crime or is still great. This does have a more than just a background of history to a fictional crime so be warned! If you don&apos;t find Roman history just as interesting as the solution to the mystery then this probably isn&apos;t the book for you. More than most of Saylor&apos;s other books Catalina&apos;s Riddle stirs up messy emotions for me. I long to get to the solution of at least one of the </span>
  <span id="freeText1286421970789632479" style="display:none">Though this is not one of the typical Roma Sub Rosa books where a client hires Gordianus to solve a murder or other crime or is still great. This does have a more than just a background of history to a fictional crime so be warned! If you don't find Roman history just as interesting as the solution to the mystery then this probably isn't the book for you. More than most of Saylor's other books Catalina's Riddle stirs up messy emotions for me. I long to get to the solution of at least one of the problems facing Gordianus. I love the lifelike way the issues are mixed together. One does not simply have political pressures and problems without any personal complications. Gordianus and his family deal with questions of overarching political importance when they play host to Catalina, as well as trying to figure out the "small" matter of a dead body or two left on their farm, with daily concerns such as a son coming of age and a shortage of hay in between. <br /><br />The most personal issue facing Gordianus is that of the changing relationship with his younger son Meto. As Meto becomes a man in the eyes of society, his relationship with his father becomes strained. Despite not having children myself I find myself both frustrated with and sympathetic to Gordianus' plight. I feel his confusion when he tries to treat Meto as a man but can't seem to please Meto; I feel his relief when he talks to his older son, Eco and so on. Saylor's ability to draw such complex emotions from someone who cannot relate with firsthand experience speaks to his skill in in rendering the relationship.<br /><br />The political problem between Catalina and Cicero is fascinating to me. I find myself wishing more and more that there were more definitive sources about this conflict as I read farther in the book. I really understand Gordianus' skepticism also. After the 2016 US presidential election cynicism and skepticism seem to be all too easy to understand. So many things from trying to bring criminal charges against candidates to riots after the votes were tallied felt like reflections of this book, though there haven't been actual battles between American armies so far!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1286421970789632479" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


