<div id="review_1921090649" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1921090649" />
    <a title="Cameron McLachlan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63459867-cameron-mclachlan"><img alt="Cameron McLachlan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483550202p2/63459867.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1921090649?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cameron McLachlan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cameron McLachlan" href="/user/show/63459867-cameron-mclachlan">Cameron McLachlan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1921090649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10797096580700589690">I was ultimately disappointed by this book, despite having read <i>Roman blood</i> and <i>the Venus Throw</i> in 2010. While the narrative is set against the backdrop of the vitriolic struggle between Cicero and Catilina in the late Roman Republic, most of the novel is set in rural ancient Etruria, where the protagonist Gordianus the Finder has inherited a farm. In and of itself this would be an okay jumping off point for further intrigue. However, Steven Saylor seems to be more interested in writing long win</span>
  <span id="freeText10797096580700589690" style="display:none">I was ultimately disappointed by this book, despite having read <i>Roman blood</i> and <i>the Venus Throw</i> in 2010. While the narrative is set against the backdrop of the vitriolic struggle between Cicero and Catilina in the late Roman Republic, most of the novel is set in rural ancient Etruria, where the protagonist Gordianus the Finder has inherited a farm. In and of itself this would be an okay jumping off point for further intrigue. However, Steven Saylor seems to be more interested in writing long winded "atmospheric" descriptions of rural Roman life compared to the mysteries and intrigue found in <i>Roman blood</i> and <i>the Venus Throw</i>. This leads to my second major criticism which is that at 504 pages, the plot meanders and takes its time; with the first serious bout of political conflict not coming until well after page 200. Overall, this speaks to a looser plot and less satisfactory experience compared to my previous experiences with Saylor. I still have <i>A murder on the appian way</i> and <i>the triumph of Caesar</i> on my shelf. I hope that when I return to Gordianus's world, there is more of a balance between plot and atmosphere. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10797096580700589690" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


