    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2323301488" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2323301488" />
    <a title="Filip" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20652629-filip"><img alt="Filip" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609965290p2/20652629.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2323301488?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Filip" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Filip" href="/user/show/20652629-filip">Filip</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20652629-filip?shelf=mystery-action-thriller">mystery-action-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20652629-filip?shelf=3-stars">3-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20652629-filip?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2323301488" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3512025382426138486">I lik Steven Saylor&apos;s (and Lindsey Davis&apos;) books because they are a beautiful blend of history and fiction. While this book was simply superb when it comes to the history side it focused on it so much that the mystery/fiction/plot side suffered for it. I knew nothing about Catylina and his plot and I found the story immensely interesting, however I couldn&apos;t help but feel the riddle itself is a mere excuse to be throwing Gordianus from one place where he can witness history to another.<br/><br/>I think tha</span>
  <span id="freeText3512025382426138486" style="display:none">I lik Steven Saylor's (and Lindsey Davis') books because they are a beautiful blend of history and fiction. While this book was simply superb when it comes to the history side it focused on it so much that the mystery/fiction/plot side suffered for it. I knew nothing about Catylina and his plot and I found the story immensely interesting, however I couldn't help but feel the riddle itself is a mere excuse to be throwing Gordianus from one place where he can witness history to another.<br /><br />I think that is my main gripe with the book - that Gordianus felt like a witness, seeing events unfold in front of him. Well, it isn't that surprising - the thing with historical fiction is that the outcome of certain events is set in stone, but it still becomes... well, maybe not annoying but it feels forced and contrived as Gordianus somehow manages to land in strangest places just in time to see the events unfold.<br /><br />Still, I can't say I didn't enjoy it as the history side of it was superb.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3512025382426138486" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

