<div id="review_3754662435" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3754662435" />
    <a title="KJ" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108406669-kj"><img alt="KJ" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612638203p2/108406669.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3754662435?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="KJ" class="user" itemprop="url" name="KJ" href="/user/show/108406669-kj">KJ</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3754662435" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4727231200378975252">I was honestly moved by the ending, which I will not spoil here - especially because it resist a simple black and white reading. <br/><br/>I&apos;ve been making my way through the Roma Sub Rosa series, and I really appreciate the way Saylor manages to connect the personal and the political in his books. Those interested in Roman history will often know the ending of the major political developments each book is focussed on, but the narrative remains engaging because of the personal struggles of the &apos;smaller&apos;, </span>
  <span id="freeText4727231200378975252" style="display:none">I was honestly moved by the ending, which I will not spoil here - especially because it resist a simple black and white reading. <br /><br />I've been making my way through the Roma Sub Rosa series, and I really appreciate the way Saylor manages to connect the personal and the political in his books. Those interested in Roman history will often know the ending of the major political developments each book is focussed on, but the narrative remains engaging because of the personal struggles of the 'smaller', every-day people who come into contact with the larger-than-life figures we know from the history books. As appears to have been the case for Greek tragedies, the impact and tension of the story comes less from the eventual outcome in itself, than from the way we get there - and what it does to the characters.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4727231200378975252" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


