<div id="review_2114148464" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2114148464" />
    <a title="Sara G" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4551268-sara-g"><img alt="Sara G" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584889509p2/4551268.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2114148464?book_show_action=true">Oct 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara G" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara G" href="/user/show/4551268-sara-g">Sara G</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13602563-catilina-s-riddle">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4551268-sara-g?shelf=src-fall17">src-fall17</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4551268-sara-g?shelf=on-my-kindle">on-my-kindle</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2114148464" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2188996100938564751">This one wasn&apos;t much of a mystery. The &quot;mystery&quot; was easily solved and pretty transparent, and made me feel a little disappointed that Gordianus the Finder was so easily distracted. What it was, though, was a great historical fiction depiction of Catilina and Cicero battling it out.<br/><br/>The title is perfect, because I don&apos;t think it&apos;s possible to know who Catilina actually was, given the lack of real primary source information aside from Cicero&apos;s diatribes. I thought the author did a great job with t</span>
  <span id="freeText2188996100938564751" style="display:none">This one wasn't much of a mystery. The "mystery" was easily solved and pretty transparent, and made me feel a little disappointed that Gordianus the Finder was so easily distracted. What it was, though, was a great historical fiction depiction of Catilina and Cicero battling it out.<br /><br />The title is perfect, because I don't think it's possible to know who Catilina actually was, given the lack of real primary source information aside from Cicero's diatribes. I thought the author did a great job with the information available in constructing his character here, and pitting Gordianus between his one time patron Cicero and the charismatic Catilina was inspired. I loved Julius Caesar's cameo appearances and seeing Gordianus's adopted sons, too. This series is so good.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2188996100938564751" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


